2500|$|On March 4, 1861, Abraham Lincoln {{was sworn}} in as President. In his inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a [...] "more perfect union" [...] than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, that it was a <b>binding</b> <b>contract,</b> and called any secession [...] "legally void". He stated he had no intent to invade the Southern states, nor did he intend to end slavery where it existed, but that he would use force to {{maintain}} possession of federal property. His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union.|$|E
